How does NAT ( Network Address Translation ) work. I've googled it and all the answers are very complex. I need it explained to me like I'm five. Thanks! Explain like I'm five.assistant

So when you turn on your computer it gets a special address like 192.168.1.1. This address is like your name. All your computer's friends know your name, but you don't know all their names. So when you want to send a message to a computer, it has to be translated into its real name. That's what NAT does. It takes the computer's address and says oh, I know this one, it's 192.168.1.1. I 'll translate that to 192.168.1.2, which is the computer's real name. Then the computer's friends know that the message is coming from 192.168.1.2, which is the computer's real name. Then the computer's friends can send a message back to 192.168.1.1, which is the computer's real name, and it will be translated into 192.168.1.2, which is the computer's real name. And so on
